{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:10:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"619"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/619"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.06,0.35,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/619"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"619"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98343"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49941"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man is being reviewed for increasing shortness of breath. Several years ago he was diagnosed with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and now it is becoming more difficult to control his symptoms. In the past 12 months he has had one exacerbation that required hospitalisation and has developed a chronic dry cough. Despite maximisation of his inhalers and 1L/min of continuous home oxygen he has noticed over the last two months an increased shortness of breath that worsens further with exertion. At rest his blood pressure is 140/85 mmHg, pulse 80/min, temperature 36.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 26/min and SpO2 87% on 1L of oxygen. His chest X-ray remains unchanged from that undertaken on discharge from hospital after his last exacerbation. Sputum cultures are negative. At rest he has increased work of breathing but does not appear in significant distress and has visible muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following would be indicated to best manage his deteriorating COPD?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase continuous home oxygen therapy","Antibiotic prophylaxis","Commencement of long term oral steroid therapy","Addition of a mucolytic agent","Nocturnal ventilatory support"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDue to the chronicity of worsening shortness of breath, negative sputum cultures, lack of temperature and changes on CXR this patient is likely experiencing worsening of shortness of breath not due to an acute precipitant. The correct strategy for this patient is to i\u003Cstrong\u003Encrease continuous home oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. In patients with COPD who experience deoxygenation at rest which is indicated by a PaO2 \u226455 mmHg or oxygen saturation of \u226488% continuous home oxygen therapy is recommended. It is important to appreciated that whilst the 02 is low at rest, it will be much lower with exercise. However as this patient is already on 1L of home oxygen it is important to maximise his supplemental oxygen therapy first before considering other management options, therefore increasing home oxygen therapy is the correct answer. Increasing to 2L/min would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotic prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this patient. In some instances where management options have been fully optimised elsewhere and the patient has had \u22652\u00a0exacerbations in the year then prophylactic azithromycin may be utilised to help reduced frequency of exacerbations. Another option would be indicated first in an attempt to improve his breathing, particularly as his presentation in the scenario is not due to an acute exacerbation but rather worsening of his chronic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencement of long term steroid therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used as apart of chronic management in COPD. Although they can be indicated in acute exacerbations to aid improvement of symptoms, chronic use of steroids are associated with too significant risks e.g. cataracts, osteoporosis, gastric ulcer formation and immune suppression. The case described in this vignette is not an exacerbation of his COPD, but rather a steady worsening of the condition. There is absolutely no role for long term steroid therapy in patients like this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite thickened secretions being a issue in those with COPD there is insufficient evidence that thinning and reducing amount secretions is associated with improvement of clinical condition therefore are not apart of the COPD routine regimen. Therefore use of a \u003Cstrong\u003Emucolytic agent\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated and another option should be considered for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUse of \u003Cstrong\u003Enocturnal ventilatory support\u003C/strong\u003E is considered in patients with COPD whom experience nocturnal desaturation and hypercapnia despite supplemental oxygen therapy.\u00a0This intervention is utilised as it is thought that due to respiratory muscle weakness, nocturnal rest of these muscle may improve daytime ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Supplemental continuous oxygen therapy is recommended for chronic hypoxaemia (SpO2 \u226488%) in COPD."],"references":["Fergusson GT. Management of refractory chronic obstructive pulmonary disease [Internet]. Uptodate; 2021 [Updated 2021; cited 2021 Oct 6]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/management-of-refractory-chronic-obstructive-pulmonary-disease?search=home%20oxygen%20COPD\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=3~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2\u003E.","Stoller JK. COPD exacerbations: Prognosis, discharge planning, and prevention [Internet]. Uptodate; 2021 [Updated 2021; cited 2021 Oct 6]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/copd-exacerbations-prognosis-discharge-planning-and-prevention?search=home%20oxygen%20COPD\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=11~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=10#H2692717375\u003E.","Gay PC. Nocturnal ventilatory support in COPD [Internet]. Uptodate; 2020 [Updated 2020; cited 2021 Oct 6]. Available from: \u003Chttps://www.uptodate.com/contents/nocturnal-ventilatory-support-in-copd?search=home%20oxygen%20COPD\u0026topicRef=112250\u0026source=see_link#H18\u003E.","COPD-X. \u201cCorticosteroids.\u201d COPD-X, 12 Aug. 2011, copdx.org.au/copd-x-plan/o-optimise-function/o3-corticosteroids/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98343"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"619"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98343"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T16:29:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T16:31:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"619"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116346"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"em